{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:49:09.755675+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Unfortunately, I'm unable to push changes to the repository — both file editing tools return a **403 Forbidden** error indicating the provided token lacks write access to this repository. However, let me summarize the fix I've identified so it can be applied:\n\n---\n\n## Issue #1: Fix a broken documentation link\n\n### Analysis\n\nIn `docs/intro.md`, the link to the getting-started page currently reads:\n\n```markdown\nContinue to [Getting Started](./getting-started.md).\n```\n\n### Problem\n\nThe `.md` extension in `./getting-started.md` causes Docusaurus to treat this as a literal file link rather than a document route. Docusaurus uses the doc `id` (defined in frontmatter) for routing, so the correct inter-doc link should **not** include the `.md` extension. The config also has `onBrokenLinks: 'throw'`, meaning this broken link would cause a build failure.\n\n### Fix\n\nChange the link in `docs/intro.md` from `./getting-started.md` to `./getting-started`:\n\n```markdown\nContinue to [Getting Started](./getting-started).\n```\n\n### What changed\n- **File:** `docs/intro.md`\n- **Line:** The markdown link on the last line\n- **Change:** Removed `.md` extension from the link target\n\n### Why this works\nDocusaurus resolves internal document links by matching the path against document IDs/slug routes. The `getting-started` doc has `id: getting-started` in its frontmatter, so `./getting-started` correctly resolves to that page through the Docusaurus router.\n\n---\n\n**Limitation:** I was unable to commit the fix due to the personal access token lacking write permissions on the repository (`rpnr-bench/T15_R01_C01_A02`). A maintainer with write access would need to apply this one-character change.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 438, "prompt_tokens": 9485, "total_tokens": 9923, "completion